500|$|Developing {{from the}} Blue Mountains to the {{south-west}} of Sydney {{in the morning}} of 1 January 1947, the storm cell was first identified at 10:00am by weather observers at Mascot. The formation of storms in this region is not unusual, especially given the hot and humid conditions at ground level which causes atmospheric instability. However, the Bureau of Meteorology reported that the formation of the storm was different from most others, describing how [...] "the underpart of the cloud was mottled and serrated or curtained, rather than , and looked angry black, while <b>false</b> <b>cirrus</b> tufts were discernible at the top".|$|E

